text:
   This series of operators allows to change the current value of variables. Placed on the answer they will act only after the reader choose it.
   Operators of action are listed bellow:

var set ["name",argument] – sets a value of argument for the variable "name";

var add ["name",argument] – adds a value of argument to the variable "name" value;

var sub ["name",argument] – subtracts a value of argument from the variable "name" value;

var mult ["name",argument] – multiplies the variable "name" value by a value of argument;

var random ["name",argumentMin,argumentMax] – sets a random value for the variable "name" in the domain from argumentMin to argumentMax;

var str set ["name","text"] – sets a text fragment "text" as a value of variable "name";

var str copy ["name1","name2"] – sets a value of string variable "name1" for the variable "name2".

   Operators of this kind can either be the requestion for availability of the answer or the limitation of variables change.
   There are following operators for these tasks:

var equal ["name",argument] – the answer is available only if variable "name" has the same value as argument ( = );

var not ["name",argument] – the answer is available only if variable "name" value is different from argument ( ≠ );

var more ["name",argument] – the answer is available only if variable "name" value is more than argument ( > );

var less ["name",argument] – the answer is available only if variable "name" value is less than argument ( < );

var need ["name",argument] – the answer is available only if variable "name" value isn't less than the argument ( ≥ );

var no more ["name",argument] – the answer is available only if variable "name" value doesn't exceed the argument ( ≤ ).

var max ["name",argument] – any change of variable "name" value is limited and can't become more than argument;

var min ["name",argument] – any change of variable "name" value is limited and can't become less than argument.

   These constructions can be used to demonstrate the value of variables to the reader. It may be usefull to make such informing answers inactive by the operator of the same name.

var show ["name"] – adds the current value of the variable to the end of the answer;

var show ["name","text"] – adds the current value of the variable to the end of the answer and places "text" (without quotation-marks) after it;

var show ["name"] and var max ["name",argument] placed together – add the current value of the variable "name" and argument to the end of the answer in the form "X/argument";

var showtime ["name"] – add the current value of variable in the form "X hours Y minutes" to the end of the answer considering the value as a number of minutes.

